segments.text: I think they had the same A&M Aggie attitude.
And I think there were some round outs and things like that that went on.
But I never participated.
I never cared to.
I participated probably in some hazing, but not a lot.
I wanted the main service that was provided.
But beyond that,
I didn't do a lot.
I just wasn't interested in it.
Did the A&M traditions remain comparatively consistent?
I think they did.
I think they did.
They began wearing fish stripes again during that period of time, which was good.
I don't think that hurt anybody.
I don't think that doing certain details, as we called it, by the upperclassmen for a freshman at all properly handled.
I do disagree with the majority of the physical hazing, but I don't think some of it is so bad.
Doing so bad, the military academies today wouldn't be doing it.
But there is a limit, and I'm willing to accept that there are strong limits.
I'm not big on this hazing aspect.
We talked about hitchhiking.
Oh, social life after the war.
Getting dates and so forth.
I did date some after the war a couple of times with some girls from Bryan.
I don't know how, somebody I knew got me the dates.
Maybe Dick Harrison.
God, I don't have any idea.
Well, there was another guy I could have done it to, I can't remember.
But I had a few dates with them, but mostly
We would go to Houston, went to TSCW with my roommate for a weekend.
He was eventually, he was engaged, became engaged to marry the girl he went up to see, and I went up with him for a couple weekends.
How did you all get up there?
Oh, we hitchhiked.
And when you were there, where did you stay?
We got hotel rooms at that point, but there were many nights, I forgot about this, we went to San Antonio to play football games and play Trinity and
Dallas, Austin, and we just spent in the lobbies of the hotels.
Lots of nights like that.
We did get a hotel when we went there.
There were court trips after the war.
Were there court trips before you went away?
Yes.
Yes, there were court trips.
And Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, and Austin?
Houston, two a year.
One north, one south?
Yeah, we didn't go to Waco at that point.
We did Fort Worth and Dallas.
And describe the routine of march, and where, and how, and so forth.
I don't remember much more than we marched from Austin.
Of course, it was down near the river, near the first or sixth street in that area.
We formed and marched towards the capital.
Houston, we marched from near then City Hall south.
The viewing stand was at the Rice Hotel, as I remember it back then.
And that would occur about what time of day?
Mid-morning on Saturday before the game.
Dallas, I don't remember where we were.
Baker Street or what we did there.
Was it assumed that every member of the Corps would go?
What if you couldn't make the Corps trip?
Was that all right?
They were encouraged to go.
No punishment?
Not that I remember.
After the war, was the routine similar?
As I remember.
It was a leisure.
After my, let's see, I guess when I was
Last of my first semester back, I got a car.
That would have been about May of 47, I guess it was.
Thereabouts, I got a car, so that made it easy.
We all shared gasoline expenses.
We'd fill up the car with three or four or five people, and we all shared gasoline expenses.
Where did an Aggie keep his car?
That time, we had parking lots near Duncan.
I think whether it's the drill field that was where we had .
But that's the general area, probably still a parking lot.
Where were there any places that were sort of off limits to Aggie students in the Brasses County area?
Well, we closed Ed's after my first semester.
I went out there one time.
Where was that?
On the old Highway 6 to Houston.
I remember it as a stone-fronted building.
I was there once and then it got closed.
Was that Hard Liquor's?
No.
No, it was Ed's.
It might have been Hard Liquor's too.
I knew it was Ed's.
What did they serve?
Beer, of course.
Was there said to be a house of ill repute anywhere in Brasses County?
Not that anybody ever showed me or told me about.
Where did y'all get whiskey?
Somehow or other we got across to
Dimebox, isn't that near there across the river?
I don't remember.
Somewhere across the river north of Bryan.
I don't remember.
I only remember how we got there.
Was it normal for anybody to have alcohol in the dormitory?
I don't think so.
I think we just managed to drink it before we came back.
I never kept any.
I don't know.
They might have had some.
Not before the war.
After the war, there was more than one bottle stored, I'm sure.
What were the important, either before or after the war, what were the important social events of the year?
Class dances.
Held where?
Sabisa.
Describe them in terms of what happened and how you dressed.
Well, just in uniform, before the war certainly, and afterwards when I was in the Corps,
I dressed in uniform, I know.
Class A uniform.
The girls were formals.
How were the girls?
They stayed in the empty dormitories that were empty for them, or professors' homes or civilian homes.
How were they treated at those dances?
I think with the utmost respect, I don't ever remember having any difficulty with that.
Were there any notable musical organizations that came?
No, none that I remember in special.
Because before the war, there were.
I've not heard of any after the war.
Yeah, I've never heard of it.
I don't know any.
Let's see.
No notable world events during your return to?
After the war.
Yeah, the Texas City disaster.
Oh, describe that.
Well, we heard about it.
We all went on top of Dorm 9.
I think we heard about it over the radio while we were sunbathing on the top roof of Dorm 9.
And we all looked towards Houston and swore that we saw smoke.
That's a debatable question, too.
I'm looking at my notes.
Other than alcohol, were there any other substances that people used that most people would have said were not permissible?
I never heard of that drug.
Cigarettes, of course.
They were encouraged.
But the advertising at that period of time, this encouraged people to smoke, and nobody thought anything about it.
You smoked the smoke.
What do you remember as the most popular varieties?
I remember Lucky Strike Green has gone to war, Campbell's.
Cigars were smoked in jail practice at some.
No chugged back and no snuff.
I don't remember those.
All right, football games after the war.
Any change?
We formed the T, the block T at home.
On the field?
On the field.
Who was in the T?
I think everybody but freshmen.
We might even have freshmen.
I don't remember any discrimination, but I know certainly the juniors and seniors were.
And that was stopped when they ran over Doug Walker at the SMU game.
The following year or two after that, it was stopped.
I think that was good and bad, but I thought it was a good formation to have.
I liked it.
Who were some of the sports celebrities of your student days?
Bill Geary, who's the president, I think, of Texas Utilities today.
He played center on the football team.
Not Bill Geary.
Bill Geary was in.
played in, Bob Geary.
G-A-R-Y.
G-A-R-Y.
Marion Flanagan, Red Burdette, football, Earl Beasley, pitcher in baseball before the, well, and then
I can't think of the name.
Hondo.
Hondo.
Hartone?
Yeah, Clint Hartone.
Not Clint, but he was punting for the football team too.
My half played fleeting.
Clint Hartone was a Giants baseball player, but he did have one.
What was his name?
I can't think of it.
Robert Smith.
Well, those were later years.
That was after I graduated.
Oh, that's right.
That's right.
I'm sorry.
But when I came back, it was Broussard and Marion Flanagan, I think I mentioned.
Stubby Matthews.
Do you remember any?
Ed Steisenberger.
Remember any special games?
Winning or losing?
Once it was Austin, Texas.
I remember those.
But other than that, as a student, I don't remember anything, what, so special.
Okay, did you?
We played, those days, we played at Olmby Stadium.
We played SMU at Olmby Stadium, and I remember.
Did you go through final review?
Yes.
Describe that, please.
Probably the best military experience I had when I was there.
I never could have had an officer
reasons.
Who knows?
Grades weren't real good.
I wasn't too outspoken.
I was an athletic officer, but that didn't mean anything as a cadet officer.
Who knows?
Whatever the reason, I don't know.
But yeah, I wasn't ever selected.
But I did have an opportunity to be a battalion commander
at the practice review, and that was a big thrill for me.
Who came to the fine review from your family?
I suppose my parents did, but I don't remember.
Was there any notable dignitary at that fine review?
Where was it held?
Well, what do they call it, Oren Simpson's field now?
Well, the drill field.
The drill field, yeah.
And then commencement, when you graduated?
We went through commencement and commissioning, but I couldn't get a diploma because I hadn't finished summer camp for ROTC.
I had a commitment there, so I went through, got my diploma and got my commission, but they were empty cylinders.
And it was held where?
On Kyle Field.
Outdoors?
Outdoors.
Was there a notable speaker at that, or the year ago?
I probably got the field at home, but I don't remember anything special that I can recall.
Every name called?
Every hand shaken?
Every hand shaken, every name called.
It was a big thrill to walk across and get commissioned and uniformed.
Let's see.
Was muster after the war there anything different?
It wasn't as impressive a ceremony as it is today.
I'm trying to remember where I was in April of 47.
Nothing special stands out.
Let's see.
Bonfire.
Describe bonfire in those days.
All I know is it got built with big logs and upperclassmen health and where the logs came from.
It was logs?
Yeah.
Alright, did you all have a bonfire during the war?
As I remember we did.
Where?
I think it was on the drill field.
I think you're right.
I don't remember it was on the drill field.
And was that trash?
Later, no.
They might have had some small trash, but most of it was still fairly good sized logs.
Not nearly as high.
Was there any kind of structure up on top?
Of course, the old outhouse was always there.
Where did those come from?
Nobody ever knew.
Especially in later years, they weren't used that much.
Did you have any special friends from that post-war time that were?
Jimmy McGregor was my roommate and I stayed in contact with him for many years afterwards.
Of course, Babe Schwartz was after the war and I stayed, and still do.
Duke Hobbs is a class agent now.
One of the bigger thrills I ever had was becoming a class agent, later years of course after the war, and long after.
Eddie Hinkle was killed in service.
Oh, Buddy Powell and I remain close friends from all the way through.
Johnny Murchison, Dick Osterholm, Paul Ostermeyer.
Handball was an event in those days, old wooden handball courts.
Trying to think how to tell you where they were.
They were just west of the P.L.
Downs Natatorium.
Wooden frame buildings that were used for handball courts.
They didn't play racquetball, they played handball.
Those were used quite a bit.
The guy who eventually married my cousin and I played a lot of handball there from Waco, Harvey Miller.
That's in 48.
Was intramurals important?
Intramurals, they weren't that important, but we participated.
I remember in softball and football, I didn't do basketball, I never could sink a basket.
But I think those are the only ones that I recall.
Did you go by train much?
No, we didn't go by train very much.
I think I had one
Several times I came back from Houston on the train late at night.
We used to run a cross-country course as freshmen, which was around the then dairy barn and I guess cattle pens, cow pens, the dusty violent six-tenths that we had to run.
The best time I ever had was after I took the
The owl from Houston got back at 4 o'clock in the morning, or maybe even later, and had to run at 8 o'clock.
I was too tired not to stop.
I know if I stopped, I'd never quit, never make it.
When you're preparing to leave the campus with your new degree, what sort of world did you think you were entering?
What was ahead?
There was really nothing ahead.
There were six jobs, as I recall, offered to aeronautical engineering graduates.

Everybody wanted the one or two or three that were offered by Chance Lawton, which was in Connecticut, because he knew they were going to eventually, they already got announced moving back to Dallas, so everybody wanted to go there for a period of time so they could then get the experience and then move back.
Again, whether the reasons, I have no idea.
Probably poor grades and a poor interview, I didn't get one of them.

So the next, and my dad was quite ill at the time, so I took the next best thing that turned out best because he was very ill. And went to work in his business, which was then known as Houston Paper Company.
Never thought much about anything more than that, except it was a job.
Did you feel that you were, that A&M had prepared you well?
Not at that time because I, except one time later years, let's see this was probably, I finished in 48 so this might have been maybe 51 or so.
We had built an addition to the building, and they were complaining because it was a hot area.
The fans weren't drawing, but they had exhaust fans.
And we had an entrance, a big 10-foot square warehouse entrance on the bend, which had been the east side of that section.
The warehouse rail dock was on the north side, and they were complaining because they weren't
I couldn't feel any of it.
Well, I finally convinced the superintendent of that area and my dad that if they would close the doors halfway, that they would feel the draft more because of the velocity of the granite.
And my dad said, you did learn something.
That's the only time I know, except for using the slide rules of multiply and divide, is the only time I felt like I ever used any of it, by education, official education.
Back to interviewing.
Did the interviewers come to the campus?
Yes.
Where were the interviews conducted?
I don't really remember.
I suppose it was...
Could have been the library.
Any special preparation that y'all made?
No, no.
We just signed up for it and dressed.
I'm sure we put coats and ties on or uniforms.
But one of the questions he asked me I'll never forget, of course, is, where would you like to be if you get this job five years from now?
And I said, well, I don't know much about the industry, so I really don't know how to answer.
I said, what places are there?
He described something, and I said, I think I'd like to be a manager of a design function.
I don't know.
I just never felt comfortable, I guess.
I never thought I felt comfortable anyway.
Aggie ring.
Did people get their rings then?
We got our rings.
If you qualified with hours to be a senior and were going into service, you could get your rings
graduation.
So we did get our rings.
I got mine in May of 1945.
I'll never forget it.
Bright and shiny, not bright and shiny, but dark, brand new.
And I remember a few periods of weeks that I had it before it went into service.
I wanted it to look old and beat up, so I would turn it upside down and hammer it into the wooden desk.
So when the gold would beat up, I wouldn't look quite so new.
I regretted it later.
And was there pride in Aggie rings then?
Tremendous.
Tremendous pride.
It cost us $39, $36, $39.
Ten carat gold.
My son got his.
It was ten times as much.
But that's okay.
He got it finally.
Let's see.
It helped me, as a matter of fact, while I was in service.
Oh, good.

There was a lieutenant colonel that was, we were in operations and he was in intelligence or some other function at the headquarters there, and when must retain, that was the story I meant to tell, I forgot.
Oh, please.
I asked my lieutenant I worked for if I could go talk to him.
So he said yes, why, and I told him why, and he said, well,
I said, but I'm scared.
He said, don't be afraid.
You have some relationship in a way.
They're human beings too.
So I went up there and did the usual military salute and asked permission to speak and asked him if he was going to the muster.
He said, what do you know about muster?
Or something to that effect.
And I said, I'm an Aggie, sir.
If you'll go with me, I'll go.
I said, yes, sir.
I'd like to go and meet some of my classmates that I knew had written that were going to be there.
So he said, meet me at some time, a certain hour in the morning, and I'll have a staff car there.
So I met him.
And the driver we had suited smartly when he came up.
And he looked at me kind of funny.
And I started to get in the front seat next to the driver, because I was the carpenter.
PFC, our carpool, and the lieutenant colonel that most were getting back with me.
So we went, and I drove in the back with him, and we drove to the muster and went to the ceremony.
And then there were two guys that I knew there from my class that I wanted to stay with, Dwayne Bennett and Ellen Gabert.
So I went to him before it was, or after it was over, and asked if I could stay.
I'd like to stay overnight.
We had no orders.
He said, well, if you get in any trouble, just tell them there's a verbal officer, commanding officer, and I'll take care of it.
So I stayed.
Where was this?
This was, well, again, I don't remember the name of this.
They had Hamburg, Germany, as I remember.
But again, I've got, no, I sent the program to the court center.
This would have been 40, 1946.
And so I can't tell you the name of the city either.
I think it was Bad Humburg.
Oh, I may have a letter from home that can tell me.
But any event, we spent the night there and visited.
And he went on back.
And I don't know how I got, I guess I did hide back.
I don't know how I got back to that.
I don't fit.
After the war on the campus, did you have the impression that the traditions were stronger than they had been?
Lister, Bonfire, Silver Taps?
No, I don't think so.
There might have been more pressure, more feeling of tradition because of those who'd been in service participated in those kinds of events.
And I think that probably made a impression on me, even though I was a lot younger.
And I'm sure it must have on the others.
So I suspect it probably did have some impact.
See, I had the impression that World War II was a kind of a special time in solidifying those.
Some of the people that I've interviewed can't remember whether muster was held before the war began or not.
They think it was, but if so, some of them didn't remember going.
Well, and I think that had a lot to do with the fact that I did not go to the first muster.
I came to Houston to see my friend, but I could have come after the muster, too.
Let's see, another question somebody told me to ask, did you live in Hollywood?
And I don't know that term.
I don't either.
OK. All right.
Running wood and water.
I don't know that one.
Plenty of water through the drowned outs and fire hoses were turned on my first two semesters, first three semesters.
Hard liquors and Uncle Ed, we know about.
Uncle Ed's, yeah.
After the war, was the student body more diverse?
Were there any more Hispanics, Asian Americans?
I don't remember whether the influx of international students came later or during that period, not this time.
I don't remember.
What about the academic rigor after the war?
My grades were better, but I think I was just more mature and could understand.
I mean, the courses I failed, I failed two courses.
Analytical math was the first that Ransdell taught.
Analytical geometry was the course he taught, and I couldn't remember.
I didn't fail that one, but the only two courses I remember failing were the only semester of physics I had to take and that English course.
That's before you went away.
That was before the war, and I made B's afterwards, which wasn't great, but they were a hell of a lot better than Taylor.
Now, in my case, I don't remember we ever calculated a grade point average.
Did y'all?
We did on a three-point, not a four-point basis.
Oh, that's right.
Yes, it was.
And so we had to interpolate later in order to figure out what ours was.
But we kept the C average, which was a one, or better.
And it was OK. All right, now we're getting close to the end and close to the serious questions.
As you look back, what did you learn at A&M that's been significant in your life?
I think certainly I grew up and matured between A&M and the military.
I think it definitely had a humbling experience for me.
Think about my family life.
My dad had his
own business.
We lived nicely.
We had cars.
My dad had a company car, even in, well, everything I can remember.
And then my mother had a car.
They weren't always new cars.
One of them, a couple of them I remember specifically, we bought from the doctor.
a lot of used cars, but later on they became new.
1939, I know we had a new car, no matter what it did.
But we lived nicely, and I didn't have that much to be concerned about.

So when I got up there and I did learn that everybody was more humble and basically the same, and you treated everybody the same, and there wasn't any difference between one and another, I think I did learn a lot there.
qualities of being an Aggie?
What does it mean to be an Aggie?

I think it's being able to meet people, to converse with them, to recognize that the secretary or the warehouseman may someday be as important as the person you're trying to do business with, so you better damn well treat them right.
And certainly if you're in the military, you have recognition of the needs and wants and desires
What are the factors that contribute most to Aggie spirit, feeling?
Commonality of attitudes, the fact that people, at least in those days, and I guess maybe to some degree today, but at least in those days,
dressed alike, you didn't know who was who, or what was what, or what they had or didn't have.

So if they didn't have it and they worked in the mess hall, and some of our friends worked in the mess hall to get through school, some of them dropped out here and there, they worked for a while and came back, fortunately I didn't have to.
But it didn't seem to make any difference who they were or what they were.
Pretty much, as far as I was concerned, everybody felt the same.
And as I said before, I never felt any religious problems.
Not to say they may not have been there.
They probably were.
